  "topic_name": "Light",
  "canonical_explanation": {
    "text": "Light travels in straight lines and has dual nature (wave and particle). The laws of reflection state that angle of incidence equals angle of reflection, with incident ray, reflected ray, and normal in the same plane. For spherical mirrors, the mirror formula is 1/f = 1/v + 1/u. Refraction occurs when light changes speed at medium boundaries. Snell's law states n1 sin(i) = n2 sin(r). Total internal reflection occurs when light travels from denser to rarer medium at angles greater than critical angle. For lenses, the formula is 1/f = 1/v - 1/u, and power P = 1/f in diopters.",
    "rules": [
      "Laws of reflection: angle i = angle r, in same plane",
      "Mirror formula: 1/f = 1/v + 1/u",
      "Magnification: m = -v/u = h'/h",
      "Snell's law: n1 sin(i) = n2 sin(r)",
      "Critical angle: sin(c) = 1/n",
      "TIR: from denser to rarer, i > c",
      "Lens formula: 1/f = 1/v - 1/u",
      "Power of lens: P = 1/f (in diopters)"
    ]
  },
